We return to our top story,
North Korea, its
missile and nuclear programs,
and the tougher

07:29.982 --> 07:33.052 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
line being drawn with the regime
by the Trump
administration.

07:33.085 --> 07:38.391 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I spoke a short time ago with
William Perry,
who served as defense secretary
under President

07:38.424 --> 07:39.926 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Bill Clinton.

07:39.959 --> 07:44.163 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
After Mr. Perry left that post,
he led a diplomatic
effort on North Korea.

07:44.197 --> 07:49.168 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I started by asking how he
interprets the
Trump administration position
that the time

07:49.202 --> 07:51.604 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
for strategic patience is over.

07:51.637 --> 07:54.373 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
®MD-BO /WILLIAM PERRY, Former
U.S. Defense
Secretary: I think it means that
they're prepared

07:54.407 --> 07:59.312 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to take more drastic action and
they're certainly
implying that military action
could be a part

07:59.345 --> 08:01.113 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
of that.

08:01.147 --> 08:04.450 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And do you think
that that's
an approach that is likely to
bring about

08:04.484 --> 08:07.753 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
a response from the North Korean
regime that
the U.S. wants?

08:07.787 --> 08:12.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM PERRY: Well, I think
that this is
an unusually dangerous time,
because of both

08:12.892 --> 08:18.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
what North Korea is saying and
doing and what
the administration is thinking
of doing.

08:18.998 --> 08:25.538 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My own view is that a military
action, while
might be appropriate at some
time, is not

08:25.571 --> 08:27.273 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
yet appropriate.

08:27.306 --> 08:30.443 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think there is still time for
diplomacy
and there's time for effective
diplomacy,

08:30.476 --> 08:32.845 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
but it must be coercive
diplomacy.

08:32.879 --> 08:37.383 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The earlier diplomacy for the
last two administrations
has been quite ineffective.

08:37.416 --> 08:42.622 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, paradoxically, precisely
because of the
dangers, I think we have the
opportunity to

08:42.655 --> 08:46.559 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
conduct some effective
diplomacy, although
this is going to be coercive
diplomacy.

08:46.592 --> 08:49.729 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And what do you
mean by coercive
diplomacy?

08:49.762 --> 08:56.035 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM PERRY: Diplomacy which
threatens actions
which are going to hurt North
Korea.

08:56.068 --> 09:01.207 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have in the -- past two
administrations
had sanctions as our element and
course of

09:01.240 --> 09:05.244 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
diplomacy, but they were very
ineffective
and very weak.

09:05.278 --> 09:12.151 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, because of the present
situation, we're
in a position to provide really
powerful disincentives,

09:12.184 --> 09:15.555 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
very powerful efforts, much more
so than the
sanctions.

09:15.588 --> 09:22.061 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The two changes are that China,
which in the
past has not shown much concern
over the North

09:22.094 --> 09:25.598 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Korean nuclear weapon, they're
now being greatly
concerned, seeing that this
could threaten

09:25.631 --> 09:27.400 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
their very core interests.

09:27.433 --> 09:32.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, therefore, I think China
would be willing
at this stage to take very
powerful actions

09:32.505 --> 09:36.709 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in their economy, like holding
back food and
holding back fuel.

09:36.742 --> 09:42.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the other hand, the threat of
military
action against North Korea in
the past has

09:42.281 --> 09:47.353 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not really been a credible one,
but I think
it may have become credible in
the last few

09:47.386 --> 09:49.255 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
months.

09:49.288 --> 09:51.724 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And why do you
think the Chinese
would be ready to be tougher
right now than

09:51.757 --> 09:53.526 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
they have been before?

09:53.559 --> 09:56.862 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
WILLIAM PERRY: They see their
core interests
being very heavily threatened
right now.

09:56.896 --> 10:02.034 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Certainly, a war on the Korean
Peninsula would
be very detrimental to their
core interests.

10:02.068 --> 10:07.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the possibility of either
South Korea
or Japan going nuclear are
really quite detrimental

10:07.540 --> 10:08.941 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to their core interests.

10:08.975 --> 10:12.945 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, having that in mind, I think
they're willing
to take serious action.

10:12.979 --> 10:15.348 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I do not see that China can
solve this problem
alone.

10:15.381 --> 10:17.149 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
I do not suggest that.

10:17.183 --> 10:23.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But China and the United States
working together
could put together a very
powerful set of

10:23.155 --> 10:29.095 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
disincentives that can effect a
coercive diplomacy
that has good chance, I think,
of being effective.

10:29.128 --> 10:35.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And when you say
the U.S. suggests
it's prepared to take military
action, isn't

10:35.534 --> 10:43.809 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
there a very real risk, though,
that the North
could go after, successfully hit
South Korea

10:43.843 --> 10:45.411 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
because it's so close?

10:45.444 --> 10:49.348 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
WILLIAM PERRY: I think there is
a very great
risk in taking military action.

10:49.382 --> 10:52.184 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And I do not recommend that at
this time.

10:52.218 --> 10:57.556 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
My point, though, is that North
Korea has
to believe there is a
possibility now, a very

10:57.590 --> 11:03.295 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
