31:28.353 --> 31:35.426 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of St. Thomas in Minnesota.

31:35.460 --> 31:46.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A cold-blooded murder posted on
Facebook on
Sunday set off shock and strong
reactions

31:46.738 --> 31:52.243 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
across social media and beyond
today, as the
manhunt for the killer
intensified.

31:52.277 --> 31:55.680 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
John Yang has the story.

31:55.713 --> 32:00.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: The 57-second video
shows a man
identified as Steve Stephens
driving the streets

32:00.218 --> 32:02.654 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of Cleveland while talking on
the phone.

32:02.687 --> 32:08.960 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
He then steps from the car and
confronts Robert
Godwin Sr., a 74-year-old
retired foundry

32:08.993 --> 32:14.832 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
worker, a father of nine and a
grandfather
of 14, and shoots Godwin dead.

32:14.866 --> 32:19.704 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The online killing reportedly
remained on
the site for nearly three hours
before Facebook

32:19.737 --> 32:21.506 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
removed it.

32:21.539 --> 32:26.077 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In a statement late today, the
company said
that the video has "no place on
Facebook and

32:26.110 --> 32:30.281 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
goes against our policies and
everything we
stand for."

32:30.315 --> 32:35.420 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The company said it's reviewing
how it operates
'to be sure people can report
videos that

32:35.453 --> 32:38.990 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
violate our standards as quickly
as possible."

32:39.023 --> 32:44.095 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This episode raises fresh
questions about
the role and responsibility of
social media

32:44.128 --> 32:46.164 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
sites like Facebook.

32:46.197 --> 32:51.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Before the latest statement, I
spoke with
Emily Dreyfuss, a senior staff
writer at "Wired"

32:51.102 --> 32:52.136 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
magazine.

32:52.170 --> 32:55.006 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I began by asking her what
Facebook could
do.

32:55.039 --> 32:59.744 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EMILY DREYFUSS, "Wired": First
of all, you
know, it is true that Facebook
is working

32:59.777 --> 33:03.314 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
very hard to keep videos like
this off of
its site.

33:03.348 --> 33:07.719 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's easy in a moment like this
to say, you
know, this is absurd that it was
on Facebook

33:07.752 --> 33:09.387 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
for even three hours.

33:09.420 --> 33:14.859 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the fact is that a large
apparatus of
content moderation and work went
into the

33:14.892 --> 33:17.729 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
effort to be able to even get
the video down
after three hours.

33:17.762 --> 33:22.200 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And in order for it to be
removed, that means
that people on Facebook had to
flag it as

33:22.233 --> 33:26.838 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
inappropriate, and then that
flag had to be
sent to people that Facebook
employs all over

33:26.871 --> 33:29.974 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
the world to get rid of content
like this.

33:30.008 --> 33:30.975 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
And they took it down.

33:31.009 --> 33:33.344 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, sometimes, this can take up
to 48 hours.

33:33.378 --> 33:37.882 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, three hours here is not even
long in the
scheme of things.

33:37.915 --> 33:40.385 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Now, Facebook could do more.

33:40.418 --> 33:43.321 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And they are working hard to
figure out what
they can do.

33:43.354 --> 33:49.460 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of those things would be to
use A.I. and
allow artificial intelligence to
help humans

33:49.494 --> 33:54.465 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
who are having to flag this sort
of terrible,
gruesome material so that we
don't see it.

33:54.499 --> 34:00.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
One of the problems is that A.I.
is not really
necessarily ready and up to the
task of that

34:00.505 --> 34:06.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
yet, so Facebook is still trying
to figure
out how to make this work.

34:06.077 --> 34:07.845 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JOHN YANG: I want to make sure I
understand.

34:07.879 --> 34:12.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They rely on Facebook users to
flag these
things, or do they have people
on their staff

34:12.817 --> 34:14.552 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
watching videos being uploaded?

34:14.585 --> 34:18.122 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EMILY DREYFUSS: So, they don't
have people
on staff who are watching videos
as they're

34:18.156 --> 34:19.991 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
uploaded.

34:20.024 --> 34:22.827 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What they have, they employ --
Facebook employs
hundreds of thousands of people
who they call

34:22.860 --> 34:27.799 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
content moderators, whose job is
to just watch
videos like this and, if they
see something

34:27.832 --> 34:29.534 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
inappropriate, to take them
down.

34:29.567 --> 34:33.471 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
However, these people are not
watching them
before the video hits the Web
site.

34:33.504 --> 34:37.341 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They're watching them after a
video has been
uploaded, and then after someone
like you

34:37.375 --> 34:42.313 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or me or anyone else on Facebook
has flagged
that video as potentially being
inappropriate.

34:42.346 --> 34:46.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
At that moment, that video will
then get sent
to this team of content
moderators who will

34:46.818 --> 34:48.519 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
look at it.

34:48.553 --> 34:52.890 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Right now, Facebook doesn't have
a system
in place to look at the video
and to moderate

34:52.924 --> 34:57.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it and to decide what's on it
and whether
it's appropriate before it hits
the Web site.

34:57.161 --> 35:02.033 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, that is something they
could decide to
do, but that would radically
change what Facebook

35:02.066 --> 35:03.167 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is as we know it.

35:03.201 --> 35:04.402 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: Talk about that.

35:04.435 --> 35:06.104 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Rapid change what Facebook is as
we know it.

35:06.137 --> 35:10.708 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They try to be -- they want to
be crowdsourcing
content.

35:10.741 --> 35:13.711 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
They want to have raw, emotional
videos like
this.

35:13.744 --> 35:15.413 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
EMILY DREYFUSS: Yes.

35:15.446 --> 35:17.982 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN YANG: But, at the same
time, they don't
want to cross the line, it seems
to me.

35:18.015 --> 35:21.085 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So how do they define what they
do and what
they are?

35:21.119 --> 35:25.356 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
EMILY DREYFUSS: Yes, so this is
an incredibly
difficult challenge, not just
for Facebook,

35:25.389 --> 35:30.828 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
but for society at large, for us
to decide
what is and is not OK to be
shared on social

35:30.862 --> 35:32.630 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
media platforms.

35:32.663 --> 35:37.969 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, Facebook has resisted calls
to say that
it is a media company, like PBS
or "Wired."

35:38.002 --> 35:43.541 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, we, as journalists, have
guidelines for
how to deal with what kind of
content is appropriate

35:43.574 --> 35:45.443 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
that we would put on TV or in
our magazine.

35:45.476 --> 35:49.780 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Facebook, by refusing to call
itself a media
company, tries to take
responsibility away

35:49.814 --> 35:54.485 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
from itself and say, look,
rather than being
a media company, we are actually
a mirror

35:54.519 --> 35:58.322 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
on society, and we're going to
reflect society
at its best and at its worst.

35:58.356 --> 36:03.394 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, what we saw yesterday with
Steve Stephens'
video was clearly society at its
worst.

36:03.427 --> 36:05.730 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
But this is a huge, huge
challenge.

36:05.763 --> 36:09.000 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And what Facebook wants to do is
encourage
people to upload video.

36:09.033 --> 36:13.838 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And it says it wants to
encourage people to
upload emotional, raw, intense
video, and

36:13.871 --> 36:15.239 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it is succeeding.

36:15.273 --> 36:17.041 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
That's part of its business
model.

36:17.074 --> 36:21.712 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But if it goes too far and
allows videos like
this one to show up on people's
timelines,

36:21.746 --> 36:25.983 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
