40:41.405 --> 40:47.445 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This becomes about President
Trump and about
the message they can send, and
less about

40:47.478 --> 40:49.847 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
sort of the local issues that
this could be
about.

40:49.880 --> 40:52.917 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Well, you both
have covered
politics all over the country.

40:52.950 --> 40:54.685 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
But, Amy, I read something
today.

40:54.718 --> 40:58.355 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They were saying that -- making
the point
that Democrats are spending a
lot of money

40:58.389 --> 41:05.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
on television and online, on
ads, but they're
not putting enough into actually
turning out

41:05.529 --> 41:08.265 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the vote, the so-called
get-out-the-vote effort.

41:08.299 --> 41:10.034 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Is this a factor here?

41:10.067 --> 41:11.836 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Are Democrats doing...

41:11.869 --> 41:14.839 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
AMY WALTER: Yes, although I am
-- you're sort
of seeing both things, the
Democrats, the

41:14.872 --> 41:18.542 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
committee that is responsible
for electing
congressional Democrats, putting
more people

41:18.576 --> 41:23.247 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
now on the ground in districts,
saying, we
understand that we need to do
more to motivate

41:23.280 --> 41:24.648 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
our base to get out.

41:24.682 --> 41:28.285 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have to go literally touch
them, rather
than to just put ads.

41:28.319 --> 41:33.958 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the fact is, this Democrat
has -- as Tam
pointed out, he has over $8
million, maybe

41:33.991 --> 41:35.326 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
close to $10 million.

41:35.359 --> 41:38.529 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's getting spent everywhere in
this congressional
district.

41:38.562 --> 41:43.434 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think this is what we're
going to be
looking for, whether the
president's low approval

41:43.467 --> 41:49.440 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
ratings and the lack of
enthusiasm from Republicans,
fired-up Democratic base, they
send a warning

41:49.473 --> 41:51.275 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
signal to Republicans.

41:51.308 --> 41:56.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
If a Democrat wins here, I think
if you're
a Republican up in 2018, you
say, uh-oh.

41:56.413 --> 42:01.385 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And it gives
heart to Democrats
if he wins, clearly.

42:01.418 --> 42:03.320 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: Yes, potentially,
if he wins.

42:03.354 --> 42:05.055 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, of course, this is just the
primary.

42:05.089 --> 42:06.991 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's sort of a jungle primary.

42:07.024 --> 42:10.194 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So if he gets more than 50
percent, he wins.

42:10.227 --> 42:13.030 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If he doesn't, there's another
race.

42:13.063 --> 42:17.501 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There's a general election which
will be a
more traditional race, where the
Democrat

42:17.535 --> 42:23.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
can go after the Republican, and
the Republican
can go after the Democrat,
though the Republicans

42:23.207 --> 42:29.246 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have been able to train their
fire pretty
much right at Jon Ossoff because
he has consolidated

42:29.280 --> 42:31.115 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
the support.

42:31.148 --> 42:34.818 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, we're looking
at kind of
a rise of Democratic energy
across the country.

42:34.852 --> 42:38.088 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have been talking about it
for the last
couple of months.

42:38.122 --> 42:41.759 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, Amy, and one other way we
looked at this
weekend -- and we mentioned it a
minute ago

42:41.792 --> 42:46.530 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
-- were these rallies across the
country,
marches pointing out the
president -- Tax

42:46.564 --> 42:51.268 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Day is coming up tomorrow, but
President Trump
hasn't released his tax returns.

42:51.302 --> 42:55.739 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The question is, though, is that
something
that gets people excited or
disturbed?

42:55.773 --> 42:57.107 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Is this something that matters?

42:57.141 --> 42:58.776 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
AMY WALTER: It certainly is
motivating to
the Democratic base.

42:58.809 --> 43:02.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And I think, for a lot of
voters, the issues
of transparency is very
important.

43:02.613 --> 43:05.849 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Despite the fact that the
president said nobody
cares about his taxes, I think a
lot of people

43:05.883 --> 43:07.551 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
care that he didn't release his
taxes.

43:07.585 --> 43:10.921 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The question issue is whether it
is the most
important issue to voters.

43:10.955 --> 43:14.758 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And it was not the most
important issue when
they decided to support the
president.

43:14.792 --> 43:19.129 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the challenge for the
president right
now is actually getting
something accomplished.

43:19.163 --> 43:22.333 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And this is why you're seeing
Republican enthusiasm
wane.

43:22.366 --> 43:24.134 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
It's the sense of frustration.

43:24.168 --> 43:28.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I talk to a lot of Republicans
who say, man,
we have the House, we have the
Senate, we

43:28.072 --> 43:29.039 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
have the White House.

43:29.073 --> 43:30.874 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We still can't get things done.

43:30.908 --> 43:36.547 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think the bigger challenge for
the president
will be if a tax reform bill
doesn't pass,

43:36.580 --> 43:38.882 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
more so than whether he releases
his taxes.

43:38.916 --> 43:43.887 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And, by the way,
the treasury
secretary, Tam, said today that
they do not

43:43.921 --> 43:49.660 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
intend or don't anticipate
getting a tax reform
plan out there before the August
recess, which

43:49.693 --> 43:50.995 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
is late in the summer.

43:51.028 --> 43:52.796 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: That's right.

43:52.830 --> 43:56.800 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And based on everything we have
seen leading
up to this point, it doesn't
look like they

43:56.834 --> 44:02.006 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have found sort of cohesion on
what they want
on the Republican side.

44:02.039 --> 44:04.842 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
The House wants something
different than the
Senate.

44:04.875 --> 44:10.447 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And the White House, I think,
has some internal
divisions even about what the
Trump administration

44:10.481 --> 44:11.448 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
wants.

44:11.482 --> 44:14.151 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, tax reform is a really big
thing.

44:14.184 --> 44:19.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It hasn't happened since 1986,
and it took
them, I think, about six years
to get it.

44:19.623 --> 44:20.591 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
I mean, it took more than...

44:20.624 --> 44:21.592 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(CROSSTALK)

44:21.625 --> 44:22.593 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Some of us
covered that.

44:22.626 --> 44:23.594 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And it was complicated and took
a long time.

44:23.627 --> 44:24.895 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: Yes, a very long
time.

44:24.928 --> 44:26.630 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Right.

44:26.664 --> 44:31.769 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: And there was some
level of
bipartisan horse-trading that is
not currently

44:31.802 --> 44:34.204 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
happening between the president
and Congress.

44:34.238 --> 44:36.940 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And if his own party doesn't
agree, that presents
a challenge.

44:36.974 --> 44:37.941 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
AMY WALTER: Yes.

44:37.975 --> 44:39.777 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And that's #governingishard.

44:39.810 --> 44:42.312 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And I think that's what
Republicans are finding
out right now, is that, even
though they have

44:42.346 --> 44:47.217 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
all the levers of power, they
have -- they
remain incredibly divided.

44:47.251 --> 44:51.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And to me, the most interesting
number that
came out today was a Pew poll
that asked of

44:51.188 --> 44:55.092 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Democrats and Republicans, do
you think your
party is mostly united or mostly
divided?

44:55.125 --> 44:58.362 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Overwhelming majority of
Republicans said,
I think our party is divided.

44:58.395 --> 45:01.965 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
Overwhelming majority of
Democrats said, I
think we're united.

45:01.999 --> 45:03.567 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
And you're seeing these
divisions.

45:03.600 --> 45:05.202 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We saw it most recently with the
health care.

45:05.235 --> 45:06.804 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And you're going to see it on
taxes, too.

45:06.837 --> 45:08.572 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: OK, less than a
minute.

45:08.605 --> 45:13.043 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Quickly to Tam on this, a story
today that
the president has done less
traveling both

45:13.077 --> 45:17.815 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the U.S. and abroad than both
of his predecessors,
Obama and George W. Bush.

45:17.848 --> 45:23.287 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Does that say something that
should tell us
anything about whether he's
going to be successful

45:23.320 --> 45:24.555 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
or not?

45:24.588 --> 45:25.989 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: I don't know if
it's a predictor
of success.

45:26.023 --> 45:30.394 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What it does tell us is, those
predecessors,
they were campaigning.

45:30.427 --> 45:34.465 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They were out pushing for policy
proposals.

45:34.498 --> 45:38.302 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Obama was out there
holding town
halls, trying to build support
for his stimulus

45:38.335 --> 45:42.806 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
package, and President Bush was
out there
trying to build support for No
Child Left

45:42.840 --> 45:45.309 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Behind and for his tax cut
proposal.

45:45.342 --> 45:49.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President Trump had about a
17-day period
where he could have gone out to
push for the

45:49.780 --> 45:53.117 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
health care bill, but it was
very much in
flux and it wasn't even clear.

45:53.150 --> 45:56.386 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He held a couple of rallies and
didn't really
campaign for it.

45:56.420 --> 46:01.358 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, he's not had the policies to
go out and
sell to the public.

46:01.391 --> 46:05.062 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
And that might be part, though
it's not clear,
of why he has spent less time.

46:05.095 --> 46:06.063 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
AMY WALTER: Yes.

46:06.096 --> 46:07.431 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
He likes to speak to his base.

46:07.464 --> 46:11.435 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He likes to preach to his choir,
rather than
convert new groups.

46:11.468 --> 46:16.807 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, his travel schedule is much
more like
comfort food than it is an
attempt to broaden

46:16.840 --> 46:18.542 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
his base.

46:18.575 --> 46:22.346 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that is going to be a much
bigger challenge
for the president going forward,
because,

46:22.379 --> 46:25.449 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
as we have seen, his approval
rating right
now right about 40 percent.

46:25.482 --> 46:28.819 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
He can't survive just at 40
percent or get
big things done with that.

46:28.852 --> 46:31.288 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: All right, I'm
getting my head
wrapped around comfort food
right now.

46:31.321 --> 46:32.289 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

46:32.322 --> 46:33.290 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
AMY WALTER: Sounds good, doesn't
it?

46:33.323 --> 46:34.825 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
(LAUGHTER)

46:34.858 --> 46:37.594 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Amy Walter,
Tamara Keith, thank
you both, Politics Monday.

46:37.628 --> 46:39.596 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Thank you.

46:39.630 --> 46:43.667 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
AMY WALTER: You're welcome.

46:43.700 --> 46:47.704 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
TAMARA KEITH: You're welcome.

46:47.738 --> 46:54.178 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now a former
American diplomat
takes a candid look at the state
of international

46:54.211 --> 46:55.546 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
affairs today.

46:55.579 --> 46:58.382 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's the latest addition to the
"NewsHour"
Bookshelf.

46:58.415 --> 47:00.217 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Margaret Warner is back with
that.

47:00.250 --> 47:05.255 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: President Trump
has discovered
in his first 100 days that the
world is as

47:05.289 --> 47:11.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
messy and menacing to U.S.
interests as he
contended during the campaign,
and much more

47:11.161 --> 47:13.664 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
difficult for Washington to
manage.

47:13.697 --> 47:17.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is the product of forces
driving the
world apart for nearly three
decades since

47:17.968 --> 47:20.037 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
the end of the Cold War.

47:20.070 --> 47:24.975 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
That's the theme of a new book
by Richard
Haass, "A World in Disarray:
American Foreign

47:25.008 --> 47:28.512 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Policy and the Crisis of the Old
Order."

47:28.545 --> 47:33.383 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
President of the Council on
Foreign Relations,
Haass served in senior foreign
policy positions

47:33.417 --> 47:35.586 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
in the administrations of both
Presidents
Bush.

47:35.619 --> 47:37.354 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And, Richard Haass, welcome.

47:37.387 --> 47:37.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD HAASS, Author, "A World
in Disarray:
American Foreign Policy and the
Crisis of

47:38.021 --> 47:39.823 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the Old Order": Thank you.

47:39.857 --> 47:42.125 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: So, as you and
I both recall,
at the end of the Cold War, we
in the West

47:42.159 --> 47:46.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
had this surge of optimism; a
new era of international
cooperation was at hand.

47:46.997 --> 47:52.102 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Instead, you write in your book,
we're seeing
a declining sense of order.

47:52.135 --> 47:53.103 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Was that inevitable?

47:53.136 --> 47:54.938 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
RICHARD HAASS: Turns out not.

47:54.972 --> 47:56.773 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Very little about history is
inevitable.

47:56.807 --> 48:00.477 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In part, though, we reflect, at
the end of
the Cold War, you had two
centers of power

48:00.510 --> 48:02.212 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
controlling things.

48:02.246 --> 48:06.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now we have any numbers of
players on the
field, lots of capacity in lots
of hands.

48:06.550 --> 48:11.088 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The United States, to some
extent, has arguably
made things worse, both by
things we have

48:11.121 --> 48:17.027 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
done, the 2003 Iraq War,
possibly going into
Libya, and things we haven't
done, not responding

48:17.060 --> 48:21.365 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to Syria's chemical weapons use
four years
ago, not following up the Libya
invasion.

48:21.398 --> 48:26.603 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then you have globalization,
the fact
that so much is traveling, the
quantity and

48:26.637 --> 48:30.173 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the speed across borders, and
the world simply
hasn't caught up.

48:30.207 --> 48:31.808 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
If anything, the gap is getting
larger.

48:31.842 --> 48:34.144 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, all this makes for a world
in disarray.

48:34.177 --> 48:35.979 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: In disarray.

48:36.013 --> 48:39.449 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You write at one point in the
book, I think
close to the end, that -- and,
as you just

48:39.483 --> 48:43.120 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
said, action has consequences,
but so does
inaction.

48:43.153 --> 48:44.988 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
And you counsel against drift.

48:45.022 --> 48:51.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, with that in mind, I mean,
what could
President Trump do that's new
about the conflict

48:51.361 --> 48:52.863 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
in Syria?

48:52.896 --> 48:55.465 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
RICHARD HAASS: Well, I think he
has to avoid
both too much and too little.

48:55.499 --> 48:57.901 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
To simply wash our hands of it,
we have seen,
would be a mistake.

48:57.935 --> 48:59.503 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We saw the refugee flows into
Europe.

48:59.536 --> 49:01.271 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
You have got all sorts of
terrorists.

49:01.305 --> 49:05.976 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
On the other hand, we're not
going to transform
Syria into a democracy anytime
soon.

49:06.009 --> 49:09.579 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We're not going to be able to
get rid of the
government of Bashar al-Assad
anytime soon.

49:09.613 --> 49:12.683 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So, what I would do is focus on
going after
ISIS.

49:12.716 --> 49:14.451 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We're going to liberate some
territory.

49:14.484 --> 49:19.523 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Let's make sure we can, with
others, make
sure any liberated territory
remains safe,

49:19.556 --> 49:21.024 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
so people can go back there.

49:21.058 --> 49:24.461 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
We don't want to have a
situation where we
win the battle and lose the war.

49:24.494 --> 49:28.765 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And we want to slowly begin a
diplomatic process,
work with the U.N., and even
with Russia,

49:28.799 --> 49:33.470 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
however strained that
relationship is, to
begin the process of saying, how
do we move

49:33.503 --> 49:37.341 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Syria towards a government that
it can live
in peace with its own people?

49:37.374 --> 49:41.845 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: At the nub of a
lot of the
crises that are confronting this
new president,

49:41.878 --> 49:47.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
let's take Syria, Ukraine, North
Korea, it
seems to me, what you really
have are tensions

49:48.018 --> 49:57.060 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
between ourselves and two newly
assertive
powers, old powers, Russia and
China.

49:57.094 --> 50:04.568 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Are we moving to a tripolar
world, in which
these three countries will all
have client

50:04.601 --> 50:06.536 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
states?

50:06.570 --> 50:08.338 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Or is it even messier than that?

50:08.372 --> 50:11.074 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD HAASS: On one level,
it's messier
than that, because globalization
is a problem.

50:11.108 --> 50:14.044 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
We have medium states, the
Irans, the North
Koreas.

50:14.077 --> 50:15.712 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
You have groups like ISIS.

50:15.746 --> 50:18.148 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I'm actually, though, not that
worried about
what you suggest, Margaret.

50:18.181 --> 50:23.220 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
I think Russia is a
one-dimensional power,
largely military force,
obviously cyber too.

50:23.253 --> 50:25.355 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
They do things in the Middle
East and in Europe.

50:25.389 --> 50:26.823 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
But we can also push back.

50:26.857 --> 50:28.658 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We can strengthen NATO.

50:28.692 --> 50:32.929 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think Mr. Putin is not going
to use large
amounts of military force if he
realizes it's

50:32.963 --> 50:36.633 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
going to be costly and
potentially unpopular
back at home.

50:36.666 --> 50:39.870 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
China's not a revolutionary
power in many
ways like, say, Russia.

50:39.903 --> 50:42.506 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
China's integrated in the region
and in the
world economically.

50:42.539 --> 50:44.641 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
It doesn't much like the North
Koreans.

50:44.674 --> 50:47.144 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think the real question is
what they're
prepared to do about it.

50:47.177 --> 50:51.281 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I actually think that China
could something
of a partner of the United
States.

50:51.314 --> 50:53.216 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
And, by the way, we should hope
so.

50:53.250 --> 50:57.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's a very different 21st
century if the
United States and China can work
together.

50:57.354 --> 51:02.325 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: But, I mean,
every past president,
at least the last two, have been
talking about

51:02.359 --> 51:04.494 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
getting China to do more on
North Korea.

51:04.528 --> 51:07.964 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
What leverage does the new
president have
that the others didn't?

51:07.998 --> 51:11.935 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD HAASS: Well, China
doesn't want to
see the United States use
military force there,

51:11.968 --> 51:17.307 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and no other president until
Donald Trump
faced a very stark reality,
that, on his watch,

51:17.340 --> 51:20.911 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
China -- North Korea is going to
be able to
put nuclear weapons on missiles
that can reach

51:20.944 --> 51:25.048 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the United States, and threaten
the lives
of millions of Americans.

51:25.082 --> 51:30.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This now -- this thing has
drifted since the
presidency, what, of Bill
Clinton.

51:30.353 --> 51:32.189 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
This is a very different
situation.

51:32.222 --> 51:36.426 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This is an urgency now, and
China has to know
that simply allowing things to
drift is no

51:36.460 --> 51:38.195 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
longer a viable option.

51:38.228 --> 51:41.731 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What I don't know, Margaret, is
how much of
the leverage they deny they have
that you

51:41.765 --> 51:44.634 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and I know they really have are
they prepared
to use.

51:44.668 --> 51:49.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Another place
in this book,
you make the comment that,
really, at the

51:49.039 --> 51:55.345 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
turn of the 20th to 21st
centuries -- quote
-- "The great powers were not so
great anymore."

51:55.378 --> 51:57.881 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Do you think Americans realize
that?

51:57.914 --> 52:02.853 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Do you think this is something
that -- kind
of a new world order, or just
sort of that

52:02.886 --> 52:04.621 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
we have to get used to?

52:04.654 --> 52:08.725 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
RICHARD HAASS: I'm not sure we
realize it,
but it's real, and in part
because there's

52:08.758 --> 52:10.894 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so many things going on out
there that we
can't control.

52:10.927 --> 52:15.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, also, look at what we have
done in things
like Iraq and Afghanistan, those
massive interventions,

52:15.665 --> 52:18.301 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
and even those two places, we
couldn't control.

52:18.335 --> 52:21.071 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
So, there ought to be a bit of
humility.

52:21.104 --> 52:24.241 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But I do think you have also put
your finger
on a big, big issue, which is,
what is the

52:24.274 --> 52:26.643 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
relationship the United States
and the world?

52:26.676 --> 52:27.878 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
We can't control things.

52:27.911 --> 52:30.180 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
We're still the single most
important country.

52:30.213 --> 52:35.352 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
What we do and don't do, what --
how we define
success in the world, more than
anything else,

52:35.385 --> 52:39.489 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
will make a difference, because
we know the
world left to its own devices
doesn't sort

52:39.523 --> 52:41.391 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
itself out.

52:41.424 --> 52:45.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Do you think
the American
public, though, is ready to
continue shouldering

52:45.061 --> 52:46.463 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
that responsibility?

52:46.496 --> 52:47.964 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
RICHARD HAASS: I'm concerned
that we're not.

52:47.998 --> 52:51.735 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
I think there's a degree of
fatigue after
Iraq and after Afghanistan.

52:51.768 --> 52:55.839 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
I think there's some
misunderstanding about
how much it costs for us.

52:55.872 --> 52:59.309 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
If you look at the inaugural
speech, the president
talked about it.

52:59.342 --> 53:03.380 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But what we're spending on
defense is only
a fraction of what we spent
during the Cold

53:03.413 --> 53:04.381 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
War.

53:04.414 --> 53:06.082 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
We can have our cake and eat it.

53:06.116 --> 53:08.618 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We can have the guns we need, we
can have
the butter, we can have the
domestic policy

53:08.652 --> 53:10.420 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
we need.

53:10.453 --> 53:13.523 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We have got to understand that
what we do
in the world is not only good
for the world;

53:13.557 --> 53:14.925 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
it's good for us.

53:14.958 --> 53:17.194 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
It's not a form of philanthropy;
it's a form
of national security.

53:17.227 --> 53:19.329 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: And that's a
case any president
has to make.

53:19.362 --> 53:20.430 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
RICHARD HAASS: Has to make.

53:20.463 --> 53:23.233 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
MARGARET WARNER: Richard Haass,
thank you
so much.

53:23.266 --> 53:31.408 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
